''Space Invaders'' was released for the Atari 2600 on March 10, 1980.{{sfn|United States Copyright Office|ref=Rel}}
It became a high seller in 1980, earning Atari over $100,000,000. The console version of ''Space Invaders'', along with popular arcade games ''[[Asteroids (video game)|Asteroids]]'', ''[[Missile Command]]'' and ''[[Battlezone (1980 video game)|Battlezone]]'' would move Atari's to a growth of $512.7 million for the year.{{sfn|Fulton|2008}} 

[[Ken Uston]] in his book ''Ken Uston's Guide to Buying and Beating the Home Video Games'' (1982) declared the version of the game as "one of Atari's best cartridges".{{sfn|Weiss|2014|p=196}} In ''How to Win at Video Games'' (1982), an anonymous reviewer stated that "Of all the available bottom-shooting games that pit you against colorful rows of descending monsters, none can compare with the one and only home version of classic arcade game".{{sfn|How to Win at Video Games|1982|p=57|ref=JoyStik}} In the 1983 Software Encyclopedia from ''[[Electronic Games]]'', the game was given an overall rating of a perfect 10, noting high rankings for single-player gaming and gameplay, while only finding the games graphics and sound to be merely good.{{sfn|Katz|1983|pp=30-31|ref=ElecGames1983}}

From retrospective reviews, ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' reviewed the game in 1989 stating the graphics were low-quality by contemporary standards and while it was an "enjoyable diversion for a while" and suggested that several other games since offer more variety and excitement.{{sfn|Computer and Video Games|1989|p=72|ref=CAVg}} In an overview of the game in ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' (2007), a reviewer commented that the game did not resemble the ''Space Invaders'' that players knew, but it had so many qualities that and was still challenging and exciting game.{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2007|p=25|ref=DefSI}} In the magazines list of the top 25 Atari 2600 games, Stuart Hunt and Darran Jones listed ''Space Invaders'' in at their 14th spot, writing that it "may not have been able to successfully emulate its arcade peer, but its vast amount of options arguable made it just as good a game."{{sfn|Jones|Hunt|p=28}}

==Legacy==
[[File:Atari-2600-Wood-4Sw-Set.jpg|thumb|''[[Electronic Games]]'' magazine said the release of ''Space Invaders'' led to Atari's dominance in the home video game market in 1980 with the [[Atari 2600]] (pictured)."{{sfn|Laney, Jr.|1981|p=32}}]]

Prior to the release of ''Space Invaders'', the sales of the Atari Video Computer System were described as "respectable, if not spectacular" while the release of the game led to what Edward B. Driscoll, Jr. of ''[[Popular Electronics|Poptronics]]'' as making not just Atari, but "the whole home videogame industry, had its [[Killer application|killer app]]."{{sfn|Driscoll, Jr.|2002|p=24}} 
The game went on to becomes one of the [[List of best-selling Atari 2600 video games|best-selling games for the Atari 2600]], with Atari video game designer [[Larry Kaplan]] saying that the console "was not doing that well -- there were only a few million in the field, and it looked like it was dying -- then ''Space Invaders'' came out, and bam! It exploded."{{sfn|Fulton|2008}}{{sfn|Buchanan|2008}} The Winter 1981 issue of ''[[Electronic Games]]'' reported that this console release of ''Space Invaders'' led to Atari's dominance in the home video game market and that it was the one title that "sold the entire [Atari 2600] system in many cases."{{sfn|Laney, Jr.|1981|p=32}} Atari 2600 sales to quadrupled following the games release.{{sfn|Goldberg|2012|p=30}} 

The success of the game lead to Atari rescheduling their entire Atari 2600 line-up from being released during the holiday season to being released throughout the year. The company also began to focus translate as many of arcade hits to the Atari 2600, starting with ''Missile Command'' in 1981.{{sfn|Fulton|2008}} Following the financial success of ''Space Invaders'', Maurer himself was compensated with a $11,000 bonus.{{sfn|Fulton|2008}} He was working in Atari's coin-op division developing a game with vector graphics that was to be a color version of ''[[Asteroids (video game)|Asteroids]]'' (1979), but stopped working on the game and left Atari. Maurer's code was picked up later by Owen Rubin and developed into an arcade game ''[[Space Duel]]'' (1982).{{sfn|Goldberg|Vendel|2012|pp=523-524}}

Along with bringing their own arcade hits to the Atari 2600, Atari also focused on licensing other popular arcade games to their console as they had with ''Space Invaders''.{{sfn|Goldberg|Vendel|2012|p=513}} Along with their own arcade games like ''Asteroids'' and ''[[Super Breakout]]'', Atari would enter an agreement to license several of [[Namco]]'s arcade titles in the United States in 1981 and in 1982, Atari received a four-year contract to distribute all current and future [[Centuri]] arcade games outside of the arcade systems.{{sfn|Fulton|2008}}{{sfn|Corderi|1982}}

A special version of the game titled ''[[Pepsi Invaders]]'' (1983) was produced at Atari that was given at to employees of the [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola Company]] at a sales convention in 1983.{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2007|p=26|ref=DefSI}} [[Rob Fulop]] would translate his own version of ''Space Invaders'' to the [[Atari 8-bit computers]].{{sfn|Goldberg|Vendel|2012|p=276}} Fulop's version also had unique elements to it, such as the invaders marching out of a rocket ship on the left side of the screen.{{sfn|Hickey, Jr.|2021|p=34}} In 2004, a hack of titled ''Space Invader Deluxe'' for the Atari 2600 was released which included the cut-scenes and color schemes similar to ''[[Space Invaders Part II]]'' (1979), using an extra 4K of rom to add a title screen and higher sound quality.{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2007|p=26|ref=DefSI}}

